<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!-- Source: 12-SummaryQual.Rmd -->
<chapter xml:id="ch-12-summary-qual" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Summarising qualitative data</title>
    <idx><h>Qualitative data</h><h>summarising|(</h></idx>
  <objectives xml:id="objectives-ch12">
    <introduction>
      <p>So far, you have learnt to ask an RQ, design a study, collect the data, classify the data, and summarise quantitative data <alert>In this chapter</alert>, you will learn to:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li><p>summarise qualitative data using the appropriate graphs.</p></li>
      <li><p>summarise qualitative data using, for example, medians, proportions and odds.</p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <section xml:id="sec-summary-qual-intro">
    <title>Introduction</title>
    <p>
      Many quantitative research studies involve qualitative variables. Except for very small amounts of data, understanding the data is difficult without a summary. As with quantitative data, qualitative data can be understood by knowing how often values of the variables appear. This is called the <em>distribution</em> of the data (Def. <xref ref="def-distribution"/>).<idx><h>Distribution</h><h>qualitative data</h></idx>
    </p>
    <p>
      The distribution can be displayed using a frequency table (Sect. <xref ref="sec-qualitative-tables"/>) or a graph (Sect. <xref ref="sec-qualitative-graphs"/>). Qualitative data can be summarised by finding modes or, for ordinal qualitative data, using medians (Sect. <xref ref="sec-summarise-data-qualitative"/>). The distribution of qualitative data can be summarised numerically by computing proportions, percentages (Sect. <xref ref="sec-qualitative-proportions-percentages"/>) or odds (Sect. <xref ref="sec-qual-odds"/>).
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-qualitative-tables">
    <title>Frequency tables for qualitative data</title>
    <idx><h>Qualitative data</h><h>frequency table</h></idx>
    <p>
      Qualitative data are typically collated in a <em>frequency table</em>.<idx><h>Frequency table</h><h>qualitative data</h></idx> The rows (or the columns) should list the <em>levels</em> of the variable, and these should be <em>exhaustive</em> (cover all levels) and <em>mutually exclusive</em> (observations belong to only one level).<idx><h>Qualitative data</h><h>levels</h></idx> The number of observations or the percentage of observations (or both) are then given for each level.
    </p>
    <p>
      For <em>nominal</em> data, the levels of the variables can be displayed in alphabetical order, in order of size, in order of personal preference, or in any other order: use the order most likely to be useful to readers. For <em>ordinal</em> data, the natural order of the levels should almost always be used.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="example-a-vstudy">
      <title>Opinions of AV vehicles</title>
      <p>
        <xref ref="pyrialakou2020perceptions"/> surveyed <m>400</m> residents of Phoenix (Arizona) about their opinions of autonomous vehicles (AVs). Demographic information (Table <xref ref="tab-a-vtable1"/>) and respondents' opinions of sharing roads with AVs (Table <xref ref="tab-a-vtable2"/>) were recorded.
      </p>
      <p>
        The gender of the respondent is <em>nominal</em> (two levels), while the age group is <em>ordinal</em> (six levels). The levels are shown in the rows. The three questions about safety (Table <xref ref="tab-a-vtable2"/>) all yield <em>ordinal</em> responses (five levels, in columns).
      </p>
    </example>
    <table xml:id="tab-a-vtable1">
      <title>Demographic information for the AV data for <m>400</m> respondents.</title>
      <tabular halign="center" top="medium" bottom="medium">
        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
          <cell></cell>
          <cell><em>Number</em></cell>
          <cell><em>Percentage</em></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell colspan="3"><em>Gender</em></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Female</cell><cell><m>204</m></cell><cell><m>51</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell>Male</cell><cell><m>196</m></cell><cell><m>49</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell colspan="3"><em>Age group</em></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>18</m> to <m>24</m></cell><cell><m>52</m></cell><cell><m>13</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>25</m> to <m>34</m></cell><cell><m>76</m></cell><cell><m>19</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>35</m> to <m>44</m></cell><cell><m>76</m></cell><cell><m>19</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>45</m> to <m>54</m></cell><cell><m>72</m></cell><cell><m>18</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>55</m> to <m>64</m></cell><cell><m>56</m></cell><cell><m>14</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
          <cell><m>65+</m></cell><cell><m>68</m></cell><cell><m>17</m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <table xml:id="tab-a-vtable2">
